            , <rs id="t17721209-9-cd46" type="crimeDate">Nov. 14</rs>
                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17721209-9-off45 t17721209-9-cd46"></join>. +</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17721209-9-person127">
                  Rachael
                   Yateman
               <interp inst="t17721209-9-person127" type="surname" value="Yateman"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17721209-9-person127" type="given" value="Rachael"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17721209-9-person127" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am servant to Mr. Mackintosh. The prisoner, who passed for a deaf and dumb woman, served the house with chips for four months; she came on Saturday night the 14th of November, about five o'clock, to see if we wanted chips; she made signs that she was ready to starve with cold; I let her sit by the fire, which she did for a quarter of an hour; she sat near a table upon which I suppose the spoon was, for a spoon was put upon that table that afternoon, which I don't recollect being removed; she staid about a quarter of an hour. A message was brought me that one of my spoons was at Mr. Wood's in the Minories; then I looked among the spoons and found one wanting.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17721209-9-person128">
                  John
                   Wood
               <interp inst="t17721209-9-person128" type="surname" value="Wood"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17721209-9-person128" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17721209-9-person128" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner came to my shop on Saturday night the 14th of November, about half<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177212090006"></xptr> after five, and offered a silver tea spoon to sale; she first said she found it in the street, afterwards she said she had it among some kitchen stuff, that made me suspect her; she told me her name was 
               <persName id="t17721209-9-person129">
                  Mary
                   Turner
               <interp inst="t17721209-9-person129" type="surname" value="Turner"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17721209-9-person129" type="given" value="Mary"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17721209-9-person129" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , and she was to be found at a glover's near Tower-hill. I stopt the spoon and went to enquire for her; I was surprised to find the woman whose name she used passed for deaf and dumb, and had not spoke for three years.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence.</p>
               <p>I was born in the Isle of Wight. I have been ill, and had a defect in my speech.</p>
